    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen there are multiple pages of the same section for one topic, `man <topic>` display the first found page. To see all the pages, use `man -a <topic>`.\r\n\r\nMy use case:\r\n\r\nI have both CPP manual and POSXI.1 system library manual (including the standard C library part) installed and  configured in `MANPATH` to search.\r\n```sh\r\nexport MANPATH=\"${HOME}/.cache/cppman:/Library/Developer/CommandLineTools/usr/share/man:/Library/Developer/CommandLineTools/SDKs/MacOSX.sdk/usr/share/man:$MANPATH\"\r\nexport MANPAGER='nvim +Man!'\r\nalias man='man -a'\r\n```\r\n\r\nThen, when I run `man va_arg` (here `man` is `man -a`), it will use Neovim as the pager to open the CPP page of `va_arg` at first, after I type `q` to quit the page, it will open the next page of `va_arg` from the C library manual. This works great. \r\n\r\nHowever, in Neovim, this doesn't work.\r\n\r\n- `:Man -a va_arg` will show error \"man.lua: manpage name cannot start with '-'\".\r\n\r\n- `:Man va_arg` only shows the first page of `va_arg`, it seems that `man.lua` doesn't respect `alias man='man -a'` either.\r\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nAdd `-a` option to `:Man` command, or add an option to configure the `man` plugin to use 'man -a' instead of 'man' as the backend command. Then `:Man -a <topoic>` or `:Man <topic>` will display all the pages found one by one like `man -a` does in the terminal (Neovim still works as the pager).",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
