            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> But you can already load manpage content in any buffer and the `:set filetype=man`. Did you try that?\r\n\r\nDo you mean I open a man page file, like `vim va_arg.3.gz`, then `:set filetype=man`? It cannot display the man page file in well format.\r\n\r\n<details>\r\n<img width=\"683\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2024-08-19 at 01 41 16\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2ec688ea-b9ff-483a-81f0-d4bfb6eef44a\">\r\n</details>\r\n\r\nAnd I'm not sure why I need to try this. I can load man page with Neovim in two ways as I said in the OP.\r\n\r\n1. Use `man` command in the console, like `man va_arg` (I already set Neovim as the pager by `export MANPAGER='nvim +Man!'` and `alias man='man -a' to load all pages of the same topic by default). So `man` will load Neovim multiple times for all the pages found.\r\n<details>\r\n\r\n`> man va_arg`\r\n\r\n\r\n<img width=\"725\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2024-08-19 at 01 53 44\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/7fd86b28-530b-449d-8bb5-f27f7c84ac99\">\r\n\r\nAfter I quit the first page of `va_arg`, it suggests there are more, I type `Enter` to continue, it will load the next found page.\r\n\r\n<img width=\"597\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2024-08-19 at 01 56 05\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/3ae17380-2423-43ef-9799-d18128cf28e4\">\r\n\r\n<img width=\"733\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2024-08-19 at 01 56 28\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/0f2bbd5d-1f4e-4a10-ae2a-85359e1aa59a\">\r\n\r\n</details>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n2. Run `Man` plugin command in Neovim, like `:Man va_arg`, it only loads the 1st found page.\r\n<details>\r\n<img width=\"730\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2024-08-19 at 02 04 50\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/181eaf89-02f9-4fa6-a6e5-5ee210ffd83d\">\r\n\r\n</details> \r\n\r\nIt would be nice for `:Man` to support `man -a <topic>` feature. ",
